IMPRESSION/REPORT/PLAN
#1 Metastatic colorectal adenocarcinoma, stage IV (T4, N2, M1), grade 3, May 11, 2010
#2 Status-post palliative right hemicolectomy, May 11, 2010
#3 History of gout
#4 History of renal insufficiency
#5 Morbid obesity
I reviewed the results of the pathology with the patient and his wife today.  I did inform him that he has metastatic disease at this time with the presence of the omental and peritoneal METS.  His staging has not been completed in view that we do not have a chest CT.  It appears from the exploratory laparotomy he did not have intrahepatic lesions; although, there were lesions superficially over his liver.  I think a CT with IV contrast of the abdomen would be reasonable upon his return visit in the outpatient setting.  We talked about the use of palliative chemotherapy in the setting of metastatic colon cancer.  The patient does not have a history of venous thromboembolism or bleeding.  Therefore, as first-line therapy I would use FOLFOX with bevacizumab.  He was concerned with regard to the financial aspect of his treatment in view that he would not be able to work during chemotherapy.  This is because of the nature of his work whereby he would lift machinery up to 100 pounds on a daily basis; and with the presence of a port and also going through cycles of fatigue while going through chemotherapy, continuing with his full-time job may not be feasible; and therefore, his insurance might run out.  I have asked him to talk with the hospital social worker to find out if he can start identifying resources for financial assistance.  The patient is interested in following-up here at KCH and also to have his chemotherapy done here at KCH as well.
RECOMMENDATIONS
1.  Return visit to Medical Oncology in approximately four weeks with updated imaging studies and labs.  The updated imaging studies would include CT of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis.
2.  I will add a CEA unto his stored serum prior to surgery.
3.  I would also add iron studies on his current labs in view that he has evidence of microcytic anemia.  He may need iron-replacement therapy postoperatively.
4.  The patient will need a port to start his chemotherapy, and this can be done as an outpatient with Vascular Interventional Radiology when he returns in four weeks.
5.  We will also consider a brain MRI when he returns for his followup appointments in view of his headaches which have become more severe recently.
6.  We will mail his appointments to his home.
Thank-you for the consult.  Please call 623-411-01350 with questions.
This consult will be staffed by Dr. High tomorrow.

