[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Dunn is a 56-year-old gentleman from 24002 44026, with a past medical history significant for gout, morbid obesity, hypertension, and renal insufficiency.
ONCOLOGIC HISTORY
1.  April 2010 -- the patient developed a severe right-sided abdominal pain after shoveling.  This was evaluated by his local emergency room, and he was found to have a hemoglobin of 9.9.  CT of the abdomen and pelvis on April 24, 2010, showed mild pericolonic stranding involving the cecum and ascending colon.  The patient was treated with antibiotics for presumed colitis.  He then underwent a colonoscopy locally on April 27, 2010, and endoscopic biopsies reviewed here showed colonic mucosa with high-grade dysplasia.
2.  May 6, 2010 -- the patient comes to Ivanhoe General Hospital for further evaluation.  He undergoes a colonoscopy on May 7, 2010, and a malignant-appearing tumor is noted at the hepatic flexure.  Biopsy of this mass confirms invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma.
3.  May 11, 2010 -- the patient underwent a right hemicolectomy for the tumor mass; however, upon exploratory laparotomy carcinomatosis with a large omental implant as well as mesenteric and parietal peritoneal implants throughout the abdomen, particularly above the liver and in the pelvis, were found.  The liver appeared remarkably free of tumor except for maybe one or two superficial and very small nodules.  Therefore, a palliative right hemicolectomy was performed.  Final pathology of the right colonic mass confirms moderately differentiated invasive grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 4- x 2.5- x 2-cm mass in the ascending colon, 6.5 cm from the distal margin.  The tumor invades through the muscularis propria and into the pericolic fat and involves the serosal surface.  Lymphatic/vascular invasion is present.  Multiple (6 of 21) regional lymph nodes are involved by metastatic adenocarcinoma.  Biopsies of the omental and peritoneal lesions were consistent with metastatic grade 3 (of 4) adenocarcinoma of colorectal origin.
Prior to surgery, aside from the abdominal pain the patient did have loose stools which is normal for him for the past several years.  He would go to the bathroom three-to-four times a day with stools of soft/watery consistency.  Caffeine made his loose stools worse.  No nausea/vomiting.  No back pain, chest pain, fevers, night sweats, hematochezia, or hematuria.  He did have chills for the past two-weeks.  He does have headaches which he feels may be associated with tapering of his prednisone.  He does have numbness in his left toes and ball of his left foot.  Occasionally, he has numbness in both hands as well. ECOG performance status was zero prior to surgery.

